<TITLE> Authorities get HC rule on Eid cattle market </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 23 (bdnews24.com)  The High Court has asked local authorities to explain why setting up a cattle market, ahead of Eid-ul-Azha, in front of Sylhet's Shah Paran shrine and its spread on to the adjacent highway should not be ruled illegal. In a rule nisi, it also ordered the Sylhet deputy commissioner, Sadar Upazila chairman and Thana Nirbahi officer to make the proper arrangements for devotees to offer prayers at the shrine. The bench of justices Syed Refaat Ahmed and Mainul Islam Chowdhury in the order, coming on a writ petition, also asked them to take immediate steps so that the market does not spread to the highway and impede traffic. The authorities will have to reply to the rule in four weeks. Advocate Manjil Morshed argued for the petitioner, Mohammed Ishraf, a resident of Khadimpur union in Sylhet Sadar. b
